    <body>&lt;p&gt;From &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.dorkbotpdx.org/blog/paul/maker_faire_2013&quot;&gt;http://www.dorkbotpdx.org/blog/paul/maker_faire_2013&lt;/a&gt;:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;margin: 0.6em 0px 1.2em; padding: 0px; color: #494949; font-family: Verdana, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; line-height: 20px;&quot;&gt;Here&apos;s a block diagram of the system.&amp;nbsp; It&apos;s from the printed handout (PDF in the files below) I&apos;ll have for people at Maker Faire.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;margin: 0.6em 0px 1.2em; padding: 0px; color: #494949; font-family: Verdana, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; line-height: 20px;&quot;&gt;&lt;img style=&quot;border: none; width: 640px; height: 294px;&quot; src=&quot;http://www.dorkbotpdx.org/files/images/mf2013_diagram.gif&quot; alt=&quot;&quot; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;margin: 0.6em 0px 1.2em; padding: 0px; color: #494949; font-family: Verdana, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; line-height: 20px;&quot;&gt;The Beaglebone runs this project easily, using about 30% CPU while the video is streaming and GIF files are triggered.&amp;nbsp; I used the efficient video4linux API, via the v4l2 library (which is installed by default on Beaglebone&apos;s Angstrom Linux distribution).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p style=&quot;margin: 0.6em 0px 1.2em; padding: 0px; color: #494949; font-family: Verdana, sans-serif; font-size: 12px; line-height: 20px;&quot;&gt;I also used libudev to detect the attach and remove events for the webcam and the USB virtual serial devices from the Teensy boards.&amp;nbsp; Each board implements a very simple identification query/response, so when udev detects each serial device, it sends the query and parses the response.&amp;nbsp; This completely avoids hard-coding any device names.&amp;nbsp; The complete source code is available below, for anyone who wants to use this technique.&lt;/p&gt;</body>
